38. omnibus aetatis suae qui tum vivebant, includes only the orators of his own times, who were then living ‚· that is, all of his contemporaries who were living at the time os the writing of the Brutus, B. c. 46. In the Brutus, 65, 231, Cicero says: quoniam in hoc sermone statui neminem eorum, qui vive- rent, nominare, . . . eos, qui iam sunt mortui, nominabo. Ac- cordingly he gives a very minute account of the orators of his own times who have passed away, but of his liviny contempo- raries he mentions none but Caesar and Marcellus. In the case os these two he makes an exception in compliance with the re- quest of Brutus. See Brut. 71, 248.
